[2] Mozambique
Date: 23 Oct 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200210230680.html>

New Cholera Outbreak in Maputo
------------------------------
At least 10 patients have been admitted to the cholera ward at the Mavalane
General Hospital in Maputo over the last few days, and the health
authorities blame the early outbreak of the disease, before the onset of
the rainy season, on deteriorating sanitation conditions in the town,
reports the 23 Oct 2002 issue of the daily paper "Noticias".
Maputo is going through yet another of its periodic garbage crises, with
heaps of rubbish piled on the streets. The menace to public health is
aggravated by leaks in the obsolete sewerage system.
The health authorities are once again urging Maputo residents to observe
basic measures of hygiene and to treat all drinking water to try and
prevent the spread of the disease.
The health source did not specify the areas from where the hospitalized
cholera patients come, but the suburbs that are usually worst hit by this
disease are Maxaquene, Chamanculo, Mafalala, Polana Canico, and Mikadjuine.
More than 340 cases of cholera that resulted in 4 deaths were reported in
Maputo during the first 2 months of this year, compared with over 800
diagnosed in a similar period of 2001.
Meanwhile, Maputo city council has announced that it will soon receive 2
new trucks to add to its mostly broken-down fleet of rubbish collection
vehicles. The director of the Maputo city sanitation services, Joao
Mucavele, said that the situation has been worsening lately because the 4
trucks that were being used to do the job have all broken down and the
municipal authorities do not have the money to buy the necessary spare
parts to repair them.
Mucavele said that until the 2 trucks arrive, the municipal authorities are
working with local business people to help in the job of cleaning up the
city. Mucavele said that for it to do the job properly, the municipality
needs at least 15 garbage trucks.
******
[3] Uganda [Cholera and Dysentery]
Date: Wed 10 Oct 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ugandan Weekly Epidemiology Report (Week ending 13 Oct 2002) [edited]

This is the summary of the epidemiological situation in the country as
reported by 100 percent (56/56) of the districts. The lowest health unit
reporting within districts was recorded in Gulu, Pader and Masindi 12, 13,
and 21 percent, respectively. Kabale, Masaka, Sembabule, Ntungamo, and
Yumbe had 100 percent health units reporting.
Cholera outbreaks have persisted in Hoima, Bundibugyo, Masindi, and Nebbi.
The number of cholera cases and deaths recorded this week is as follows:
Nebbi (31 cases with 1 death), Bundibugyo (15 cases with 3 deaths), Hoima
(2 cases) and Masindi (3 cases). The District Health Teams are urged to
step up control measures in order to minimize the impact of the epidemics.
Dysentery cases were reported in 52 districts, with those from the northern
region still leading in number of cases. The leading districts in dysentery
case reporting were: Arua (94), Moyo (64), Bundibugyo (61), Nebbi (50),
Yumbe (44), Tororo (39), Mukono (32), Nakapiripiriti (30), Kumi (29 with 1
death) and Masindi (29). The District Health Teams are urged to work with
the district political leaders in the improvement of sanitation practices.
******
[4] India
Date: Mon, 28 Oct 2002 12:40:53 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: NDTV.com [edited]
<http://www.ndtv.com/morenews/showmorestory.asp?slug=Cholera+outbreak+in+Kerala%2C+infant+dies&id=31392>

The outbreak of cholera in parts of the Kerala coastal belt claimed its
first victim when a 3-day-old infant died in a government hospital on Sun
27 Oct 2002. District health authorities have confirmed that the newborn
died due to cholera at the SAT hospital in the city. The mother of the
baby is a resident of Vizinjam, where suspected cholera cases were first
reported.
Meanwhile, the state government has stepped up measures to contain the
spread of the disease in the district, where 9 cases of cholera have been
confirmed so far.
